    { question: "What is the most common type of finance for professional services firms?", answer: "Debtor finance (invoice finance) is among the most common because it directly addresses the core timing problem: work is done and invoiced, but payment takes 30-90 days. The lender advances up to 85% of eligible invoice value, assessed on the debtor's creditworthiness rather than the firm's own balance sheet. Unsecured loans and lines of credit are also common for growth, technology investment and fitout costs." },
    { question: "Can a professional services firm get finance without property security?", answer: "Yes. Many options do not require property security. Unsecured business loans, lines of credit and debtor finance are all available without property as collateral. Unsecured products may have higher rates (from 14.45% p.a.) and shorter terms, but they suit firms that do not want to tie up personal or business property." },
    { question: "How does debtor finance work for a law firm or consultancy?", answer: "The firm issues invoices to its clients on standard payment terms. The debtor finance lender assesses the creditworthiness of those clients, not the firm itself. If approved, the lender advances up to 85% of eligible invoice value within 24-48 hours. When the client pays, the balance (minus fees) is remitted. The firm can choose confidential funding (clients not notified) or disclosed factoring depending on the product." },
    { question: "Can I get finance for a practice acquisition or partner buy-out?", answer: "Yes. Practice acquisition and partner buy-outs are common funding scenarios in professional services. They typically require a secured business loan or commercial loan with a clear valuation of the practice, two years of financial statements, partnership documentation and cash flow projections. Some lenders and brokers specialise in practice finance and understand goodwill valuation, recurring revenue models and partnership structures." },
    { question: "What is the best funding option for hiring staff ahead of a contract?", answer: "A line of credit or unsecured business loan may suit this scenario. A line of credit (from 14.55% p.a.) allows the firm to draw down funds as needed and only pay interest on what is used. This is useful when the exact timing of recruitment costs is uncertain. For a known one-off hiring cost with a clear repayment source (e.g. a confirmed contract), an unsecured term loan may provide predictability." },
    { question: "Are professional services firms considered lower risk by lenders?", answer: "Professional services was identified as one of the most resilient SME sectors in Australia in the 2025-2026 period, alongside health care and business services. Firms tend to hold higher cash buffers and have more predictable revenue through retainer and recurring engagement models. This can work in their favour, but lenders still assess revenue stability, client concentration, utilisation rates and bank conduct." },
    { question: "Do I need full financial statements to apply for professional services finance?", answer: "Not always. For debtor finance and many non-bank unsecured loans, lenders assess on bank statements (3-6 months), debtor reports and basic business information rather than requiring full financial statements. For larger practice acquisitions or partnership buy-outs, lenders will typically request two years of financial statements, tax returns and BAS." },
    { question: "Does Comparison One guarantee professional services finance approval?", answer: "No. Approval, rates, terms, fees and timing depend on lender criteria and the business circumstances. Comparison One provides general information and comparison pathways only. It is not a lender and does not make credit decisions." }
